{"title":"MeetDot: Videoconferencing with Live Translation Captions","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Live multilingual videoconference captions must be accurate, low-latency, and stable, but streaming ASR→MT with re-translation causes frequent caption revisions (flicker) that increase cognitive load.","method":"Deploy a modular, cascaded streaming ASR→MT system (swap-in Kaldi/WeNet/Google ASR and DiDi/Google MT) that retranslates on each ASR update, augmented with anti-flicker captioning policies: translate-k/translate-t throttling, mask-k (using Mask-0 at utterance start then Mask-4), preserving linebreaks, and smooth pixel-wise scrolling. Further reduce instability by modifying OpenNMT CTranslate2 decoding with biased beam search to favor consistency with the previous MT output, and improve readability with NVIDIA NeMo punctuation/casing. On in-house meeting data, biased decoding lowers translation lag, normalized erasure, and word-burstiness versus un-biased MT."},{"problem":"Existing intrinsic metrics (e.g., BLEU, translation lag, erasure) do not fully capture the user experience of incremental captions in meetings, and there is a lack of practical extrinsic evaluation for end-to-end captioning quality.","method":"Provide an integrated evaluation suite that computes standard metrics plus new, videoconferencing-specific intrinsic metrics: initial lag (time to first word), incremental caption lag (update cadence), and mean/max word burstiness (words/characters added or removed per update). Introduce a cross-lingual, Taboo-style word-guessing game with automatic scoring to A/B test captioning algorithms and configurations, serving as an extrinsic measure of real-time communicative effectiveness."}]}
